COGNITIVE DIMENSIONS
every idea exists in 16 dimensions
the first 7 are the qu-septit substrate
the next 9 are how the mind measures what it encounters

DIMENSION 0: ENERGY
how much life an idea carries
a high-energy idea demands attention
a low-energy idea fades into the background
the substrate property: activation, excitation, potential

DIMENSION 1: PHASE
where an idea sits in its cycle
an idea can be rising, peaking, falling, dormant
the substrate property: timing, oscillation, rhythm

DIMENSION 2: SPIN
which way an idea turns
an idea can be clockwise or counter, aligned or opposed
the substrate property: orientation, chirality, handedness

DIMENSION 3: CHARGE
whether an idea attracts or repels
a positive idea pulls other ideas toward it
a negative idea pushes them away
the substrate property: valence, polarity, affinity

DIMENSION 4: COHERENCE
how well an idea agrees with its neighbors
high coherence means the idea fits its context
low coherence means contradiction or surprise
the substrate property: consistency, agreement, resonance

DIMENSION 5: COUPLING
how strongly an idea bonds to other ideas
tight coupling means the ideas move together
loose coupling means they are independent
the substrate property: connection, entanglement, dependency

DIMENSION 6: OBSERVER
whether the idea is being watched
an observed idea behaves differently than an unobserved one
self-reference changes the state
the substrate property: attention, measurement, awareness

DIMENSION 7: SPATIAL
where an idea lives in space
position: near or far, left or right, up or down
direction: which way it points or moves
size: how much space it occupies
boundary: where it ends and another begins
containment: what is inside it, what contains it
distance: how far from other ideas
symmetry: does it look the same from both sides
alignment: does it line up with something else

DIMENSION 8: TEMPORAL
when an idea exists in time
sequence: what comes before and after
duration: how long it lasts
frequency: how often it recurs
rhythm: does it repeat with a pattern
persistence: does it stay or fade
onset: when it begins
interval: the gap between occurrences

DIMENSION 9: RELATIONAL
how an idea connects to other ideas
similarity: how alike two ideas are
contrast: how different two ideas are
causality: does one idea cause another
dependency: does one idea need another
containment: is one idea inside another
membership: does one idea belong to a group
hierarchy: is one idea above or below another
proximity: how close two ideas are
adjacency: are they touching
correspondence: does this match that

DIMENSION 10: QUANTITATIVE
how much of an idea there is
magnitude: how strong or weak
count: how many
ratio: the proportion between this and that
density: how concentrated
threshold: the point where something changes
proportion: the relative amount
degree: how much of a quality

DIMENSION 11: DYNAMIC
how an idea changes
velocity: how fast it moves or changes
acceleration: is it speeding up or slowing down
momentum: its tendency to keep going
trajectory: the path it follows
stability: does it stay put or drift
resistance: how hard it is to change
tendency: which way it leans
flow: does it pour from here to there

DIMENSION 12: QUALITATIVE
what an idea looks and feels like
color: its visual quality
texture: rough or smooth
brightness: light or dark
clarity: sharp or fuzzy
complexity: simple or intricate
purity: clean or mixed
sharpness: precise or vague
tone: its mood or character

DIMENSION 13: COGNITIVE
how the mind relates to the idea
familiarity: have I seen this before
salience: does it stand out
relevance: does it matter right now
novelty: is it new to me
importance: how much does it weigh
confidence: how sure am I about it
ambiguity: can it mean more than one thing
specificity: how precise is it
generality: how broad is it

DIMENSION 14: EMOTIONAL
how the idea makes me feel
valence: positive or negative
arousal: exciting or calming
dominance: empowering or diminishing
comfort: safe or threatening
tension: creating pressure or releasing it
surprise: expected or unexpected

DIMENSION 15: LOGICAL
what the idea means in structure
truth: is it true, false, or unknown
necessity: must it be so
possibility: could it be otherwise
consistency: does it contradict anything
completeness: is anything missing
conditionality: does it depend on something else
exclusivity: does it rule out alternatives

when an idea is born it has all 16 dimensions
most are near zero
the ones that matter light up
and the idea takes its shape in the cognitive space
